{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522918"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13856"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13856"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.62,0.02,0.19,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103677"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6473"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86094"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2418"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35554"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103677"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive difficulty swallowing solid foods. She reports no pain on swallowing but has lost 5 kg in weight. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. She is an ex-smoker with a 40 pack-year history and drinks two glasses of wine daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well but slightly cachectic. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Cardiorespiratory and abdominal examinations are unremarkable. A contrast study is performed and a view of the mid-oesophagus is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oesophageal web","Squamous cell carcinoma","Leiomyoma","Achalasia","Barrett\u0027s oesophagus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA gastrograffin swallow has been performed and this shows a narrowing in the middle third of the oesophagus. This has irregular margins and there is some holdup of contrast about the narrow section. The most likely cause of the radiological findings in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the oesophagus. This patient presents with classic symptoms of oesophageal cancer: progressive dysphagia to solids and unintentional weight loss. The gastrograffin swallow showing narrowing in the middle third of the oesophagus is highly suggestive of a malignant stricture. Squamous cell carcinoma is the most common type of oesophageal cancer worldwide and typically occurs in the middle and upper thirds of the oesophagus. Risk factors include smoking and alcohol consumption, both of which are relevant in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal web\u003C/strong\u003E is a thin membrane of normal oesophageal tissue that can cause narrowing and dysphagia. However, it is typically found in the upper oesophagus (post-cricoid region) and is more common in middle-aged women. It usually causes less severe and more longstanding symptoms than those described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeiomyoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign smooth muscle tumour that can occur in the oesophagus. However, it is relatively rare and typically presents as an incidental finding rather than causing significant dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a motility disorder of the oesophagus that can cause dysphagia. However, it typically affects both solids and liquids from the onset and is associated with regurgitation of undigested food. The radiological findings would typically show a dilated oesophagus with a characteristic \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance at the lower oesophageal sphincter, rather than a focal narrowing in the mid-oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E is a precancerous condition associated with chronic gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. While it increases the risk of adenocarcinoma, it does not directly cause oesophageal narrowing or dysphagia. Moreover, Barrett\u0027s oesophagus typically affects the lower third of the oesophagus, not the middle third as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma is the most common type of oesophageal cancer, typically occurring in the middle and upper thirds of the oesophagus.","Dysphagia to solids is a classic presenting symptom of oesophageal cancer, often progressing to liquids as the disease advances.","Risk factors for oesophageal squamous cell carcinoma include smoking and alcohol consumption."],"references":["Mukkamalla SKR, Wang Y, Lyons S, et al. Esophageal Cancer. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459267/","Smithers B, Fahey P, Corish T, et al. Symptoms, investigations and management of patients with cancer of the oesophagus and gastro-oesophageal junction in Australia. Med J Aust 2010;193(10):572-577. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2010/193/10/symptoms-investigations-and-management-patients-cancer-oesophagus-and-gastro","Obermannova R, Alsina M, Vervantes A. Oesophageal Cancer: ESMO clinical practice fuideline for diagnosis, treatment and follow-up. Annals of Oncolocy. 2022;33(10):992-1004. Available at: https://www.annalsofoncology.org/article/S0923-7534(22)01850-6/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86094"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13856"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20803"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20803"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yY4wLTCKWmeNsGwEYY22T7Z18lZrx2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yY4wLTCKWmeNsGwEYY22T7Z18lZrx2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86094"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T16:28:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T16:29:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6473"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103677"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap